{
  "doc_id": "18342",
  "text": "In this section we tackle Criterion 7 (incremental learning), which states that a computational model of human feature learning should be sensitive to the order that objects are presented. A common assumption (and criticism; see, e.g., [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] ) of Bayesian models is that the probability of a sequence of objects is exchangeable, meaning that the model assigns the same probability to any order of the objects. 23 As human category and feature learning are sensitive to the order that information is presented [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] , order effects are a challenge for Bayesian models that assume exchangeability. This includes the models in our framework, which also assume exchangeability and are thus unable to produce order effects.",
